'''Paul Simon Wellens''' (born 27 February 1980) is an English professional former [[rugby league]] coach who was the head coach of [[St Helens RFC|St Helens]] in the [[Super League]] and a former professional [[rugby league]] footballer. He is assistant coach of [[North Queensland Cowboys]] in the [[NRL]].

A [[Great Britain national rugby league team|Great Britain]] and [[England national rugby league team|England international]] {{rlp|fb}}, he played his entire career with [[St Helens R.F.C.|St Helens]], with whom he won several [[Super League]] championships and [[Challenge Cup]] titles.<ref name="Statistics at rugbyleagueproject.org"/> Wellens also became only the third player to have won the [[Lance Todd Trophy]], [[Harry Sunderland Trophy]] and the [[Man of Steel Award]].

==Early life==
Born in [[St Helens, Merseyside|St Helens]], Wellens was educated by the [[De La Salle School, St Helens|De La Salle Christian Brothers]], along with his twin sister Claire who as of 2018 is a Drama teacher at De La Salle.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}

===Playing career===
Wellens joined the [[St Helens R.F.C.|St. Helens]] ranks and made his [[Super League]] début in the 1999's [[Super League IV]]. Success quickly followed and Wellens soon secured his place in perhaps St. Helens strongest{{citation needed|date=February 2020}} era. Wellens became renowned for his all round game, excelling particularly at taking catches. An England call-up followed and with {{rlp|fb}} [[Kris Radlinski]] already established at international level, Wellens displayed his versatility with spells on the {{rlp|wg}} and at {{rlp|ce}}. A call-up for [[Great Britain national rugby league team|Great Britain]] ensued, and he made a handful of appearances before being contentiously{{citation needed|date=February 2020}} left out by then coach [[David Waite]], who felt Wellens' form had dipped{{citation needed|date=February 2020}} during this period. Wellens played for [[St Helens R.F.C.|St. Helens]] from the interchange bench in their [[1999 Super League Grand Final]] victory over [[Bradford Bulls]].

====2000s====
Having won the 1999 Championship, St Helens contested in the [[2000 World Club Challenge]] against [[National Rugby League]] Premiers the [[Melbourne Storm]], with Wellens playing at {{rlp|hk}} in the loss. Wellens played for St Helens at {{rlp|fb}} in their [[2000 Super League Grand Final]] victory over [[Wigan Warriors|Wigan]], and in their [[2001 World Club Challenge]] victory against the [[Brisbane Broncos]].{{citation needed|date=August 2023}}

Wellens played for St Helens at fullback in their [[2002 Super League Grand Final]] victory against [[Bradford Bulls]] but was forced to leave the field after just two minutes with a broken cheekbone, which ruled him out of Great Britain's international series against [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] the following month.<ref>{{cite web | title=Wellens injury saddens Sculthorpe | website=BBC Sport | date=2002-10-22 | url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_league/2350319.stm | access-date=2023-02-02}}</ref> With a point to prove, Wellens became one of Super League's most notable performers and made the [[Rugby league positions#Fullback|number 1 jersey]] his own at international level. His attitude and aptitude to the game earned him a reputation as a model professional. As one of the quieter members of a squad littered with big names and personalities, it was all the more creditable that Wellens earned St Helens player of the season award in 2004 to underline his value at [[Knowsley Road]], establishing himself as one of the fans' favourites. Wellens was selected in the Great Britain team to compete in the end of season [[2004 Rugby League Tri-Nations]] tournament. He played a starring role at fullback where they defeated World champions [[Australia]] in game 5 24-12,  In the final against [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] he played at fullback in the Lions' 44–4 loss.{{citation needed|date=August 2023}}

In the 2006 season which would see St Helens collect all three major honours at domestic level, Wellens' own form was rewarded with the Rugby League Writers' Association player of the year, Super League players' player of the year and the prestigious [[Man of Steel Award]]. Wellens played for St Helens at fullback in their [[2006 Challenge Cup]] Final victory against [[Huddersfield Giants|Huddersfield]]. He was also awarded the [[Harry Sunderland Trophy]] as man of the match against [[Hull F.C.]] in 2006's [[Super League XI]] Grand Final. As 2006 Super League champions, St Helens faced 2006 NRL Premiers [[Brisbane Broncos]] in the [[2007 World Club Challenge]]. Wellens played at fullback in the Saints' 18–14 victory.{{citation needed|date=August 2023}}
[[File:Paul Wellens.JPG|thumb|left|100px|Wellens representing England at the [[2008 Rugby League World Cup]].]] 
In 2007 Wellens continued his form, but added another dimension to his game by becoming one of the league's top try scorers. This was highlighted in the [[Millennium Magic]] weekend victory against rivals [[Wigan Warriors|Wigan]], in which Wellens scored four tries. He was named in the end of season [[Super League Dream Team]] for the third season running. He also became joint winner of the [[Lance Todd Trophy]] award in the [[2007 Carnegie Challenge Cup]] Final against the [[Catalans Dragons]] at [[Wembley Stadium]], sharing the prize with [[Leon Pryce]]. In the [[2008 Challenge Cup Final]], Wellens retained the [[Lance Todd Trophy]] award.

Wellens was selected for the [[England national rugby league team|England squad]] to compete in the [[2008 Rugby League World Cup]] in Australia. In [[2008 Rugby League World Cup Group A|Group A]]'s first match against [[Papua New Guinea national rugby league team|Papua New Guinea]] he played at fullback in England's victory.

In January 2009, Wellens played in his own testimonial match against [[Wakefield Trinity]].
[[File:Paul Wellens Saints.JPG|thumb|right|300px|Wellens playing for St Helens in 2010]]
He played in the [[2009 Super League Grand Final]] defeat by the [[Leeds Rhinos]] at [[Old Trafford]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Fletcher|first=Paul|title=St Helens 10-18 Leeds Rhinos|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_league/8290503.stm|access-date=22 November 2019|newspaper=BBC Sport|date=10 October 2009}}</ref>

====2010s====
In 2011, Wellens was named joint captain of St. Helens alongside [[James Graham (rugby league)|James Graham]]. He took over as sole captain following Graham's departure to [[Canterbury Bulldogs]].

He played in the [[2011 Super League Grand Final]] defeat by the [[Leeds Rhinos]] at [[Old Trafford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2011/oct/08/super-league-grand-final-match-report?newsfeed=true|title=Leeds claim Grand Final glory as inspired Rob Burrow sinks St Helens|date=8 October 2011|work=The Guardian|access-date=21 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/rugbyleague/8815944/St-Helens-16-Leeds-32-match-report.html|title=St Helens 16 Leeds 32|date=8 October 2011|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=21 November 2019}}</ref>

In 2014, Wellens made history by scoring the 1,000th point in his career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.superleague.co.uk/article/29968/saints-and-wellens-go-marching|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413155734/http://www.superleague.co.uk/article/29968/saints-and-wellens-go-marching|archive-date=2014-04-13|title=SAINTS AND WELLENS GO MARCHING ON}}</ref> St Helens reached the [[2014 Super League Grand Final]], and Wellens captained them from fullback in what was a record-equalling 10th grand final appearance.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cartwright|first1=Phil|title=St Helens v Wigan as it happened|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/live/rugby-league/29416637|access-date=12 October 2014|work=[[BBC Sport]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=11 October 2014}}</ref> Saints defeated [[Wigan Warriors]] 14–6 to win their first Super League title in 8 years, with Wellens lifting the trophy.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/rugbyleague/11156623/St-Helens-14-Wigan-Warriors-6-Moment-of-madness-from-Wales-international-Ben-Flower-costs-Wigan-dear.html|title= St Helens 14 Wigan Warriors 6: Moment of madness from Wales international Ben Flower costs Wigan dear|date= 11 October 2014 |work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=15 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/oct/11/st-helens-wigan-super-league-grand-final-match-report|title= St Helens win Grand Final after Wigan's Ben Flower is sent off|date= 11 October 2014 |work=The Guardian |access-date=15 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/rugby-league/29559845|title= St Helens 14–6 Wigan Warriors|date= 11 October 2014 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=15 October 2014}}</ref>

Following a failure to recover from a long-standing hip injury, Wellens announced his retirement from playing on 24 June 2015.<ref>{{cite web | title=St Helens legend Wellens retires | website=BBC Sport | date=2015-06-24 | url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/rugby-league/33230993 | access-date=2023-02-02}}</ref> In total he played 495 times for St Helens, in the process winning 5 [[Super League]] titles, 5 [[Challenge Cup]] winners medals, two [[World Club Challenge]]s, the [[Man of Steel Award]], the [[Lance Todd Trophy]], the [[Harry Sunderland Trophy]], and was named in the [[Super League Dream Team]] on four occasions.

==Coaching career==
===St Helens===
On 18 February 2023, Wellens coached St Helens to their shock 13-12 victory over [[Penrith Panthers]] in the [[2023 World Club Challenge]].<ref>{{cite news |title=St Helens stun Penrith to win World Club Challenge |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/64666651 |work=BBC Sport}}</ref>
In his first full season in charge, Wellens guided St Helens to a third placed finish on the table. The club would lose their semi-final match against the [[Catalans Dragons]] on the full-time siren which ended their four-year reign as champions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sthelensstar.co.uk/sport/23856044.paul-wellens-q-saints-review-year-look-2024/|title=Paul Wellens Q&A: Saints review of year and a look to 2024|website=www.sthelensstar.co.uk|date=14 October 2023 }}</ref>
Wellens second season in charge of St Helens was a disappointing one with the club finishing sixth on the table, their lowest finish in the Super League era. During the season, the club also lost five games in a row. It was the first time since the Super League era began that the club had lost five consecutive games in the league. St Helens would be eliminated in the playoffs against Warrington in golden point extra-time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seriousaboutrl.com/st-helens-confirm-seven-player-exits-with-one-major-name-omitted-from-list-97627/|title=St Helens confirm seven player exits with one major name omitted from list|website=www.seriousaboutrl.com}}</ref>
In the 2025 Super League season, Wellens guided St Helens to 5th on the table. Wellens would take St Helens to one game from the grand final before they were defeated by [[Hull Kingston Rovers]] 20-12.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/articles/c04q6rqyrv6o/|title=Retiring Waerea-Hargreaves set to miss Grand Final|website=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> His contract wasn't renewed at the conclusion of his third year of coaching St Helens, confirmed in a club Statement on 9 October 2025.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/rugby-league/articles/c30qe627jl0o/|title=Head coach Wellens departs St Helens|website=www.bbc.com}}</ref>

===North Queensland Cowboys===
On 2 November 2025 it was reported that he had taken a role of assistant coach at [[NRL]] side [[North Queensland Cowboys]]<ref>{{cite web|website=Total RL|date=2 Nov 2025|accessdate=3 Nov 2025|author=Stephen Ibbetson|title=Ex-St Helens boss Paul Wellens appointed to NRL coaching role|url=https://www.totalrl.com/ex-st-helens-boss-paul-wellens-appointed-to-nrl-coaching-role/}}</ref>

